sbol:Collection.dcterms:title: iGEM Parts Registry
sbol:Collection.dcterms:description: The iGEM Registry is a growing collection of genetic parts that can be mixed and matched to build synthetic biology devices and systems. As part of the synthetic biology community's efforts to make biology easier to engineer, it provides a source of genetic parts to iGEM teams and academic labs.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_K1631024
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: Colicin-E3, its immunity protein, and colicin lysis protein is constitutively expressed strong.(under BBa_?J23101) When this device works, Colicin-E3 will be released to media, and E. coli strains which does not have immunity protein will be killed.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Yuto Yamanaka

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_K1631003
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:description: Tlanslational unit of Colicin Lysis Protein (for colicin-E3)
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription:
Colicin lysis protein allows colicins to be released. The mechanism how the colicin lysis protein allows colicin release has not been fully elucidated, but it is sure that this protein raise membrane permiability and cause quasilysis.[1]
Colicins are a cytotoxins which are released to environment and kill other related strains.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Yuto Yamanaka

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_K1631002
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription:
Colicin-E3 cleave 16SrRNA at a specific site. This activity is inhibited by immunity protein for Colicin-E3(BBa_). When lysis protein for Colicin-E3(BBa_) is co-expressed, Colicin-E3 is emited to environment and kill other strain.
Colicin is a type of bacteriocin produced by Escherichia coli.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Yuto Yamanaka

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_K1631004
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:description: Tlanslational unit of Immunity protein for Colicin-E3
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription:
Immunity protein for Colicin-E3 binds in between the Translocation domain and Ctalitic domain. Curiously, immunity protein does not block the active site.[1] It is considered that immunity protein blocks access of this enzyme to the ribosome.
Colicins are a cytotoxins which are released to environment and kill other related strains.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Yuto Yamanaka

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_B0010
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: Transcriptional terminator consisting of a 64 bp stem-loop.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Randy Rettberg

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_B0012
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: Transcription terminator for the E.coli RNA polymerase.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Reshma Shetty
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: Derived from the TE terminator of T7 bacteriophage between Genes 1.3 and 1.4 <genbank>V01146</genbank>.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes:
Suggested by Sri Kosuri and Drew Endy as a high efficiency terminator. The 5' end cutoff was placed immediately after the TAA stop codon and the 3' end cutoff was placed just prior to the RBS of Gene 1.4 (before AAGGAG).

Use anywhere transcription should be stopped when the gene of interest is upstream of this terminator.
